meta.TITLE: Rhabdomyosarcoma of Quadriceps Femoris
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Presented with a lump in the right thigh, which rapidly increased in size.  A biopsy of the mass showed a rhabdomyosarcoma of alveolar type.  A wide local excision was performed.  The patient died with multiple metastases one year later.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A section through the surgical excision specimen showing a lobulated apparently circumscribed tumour attached to the quadriceps muscle.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological section showed a tumour composed of poorly defined groups of hyperchromatic cells with only occasional cells showing evidence of differentiation to muscle cells.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Rhabdomyosarcoma is an uncommon tumour mainly affecting children and young adults.  Recent advances in chemotherapy have markedly improved prognosis for this tumour particularly in young children.

meta.TITLE: Muscular Dystrophy
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: This man suffered from facio-scapulo-humeral muscular dystrophy, beginning in late childhood and slowly progressive throughout life.  One brother and possibly one of the patient's children were similarly affected.  By age 70 he was able to walk on flat surfaces and needed assistance to dress.  He had marked muscle wasting in the limbs.  Death was due to disseminated malignant melanoma following a primary skin melanoma excised only 8 months prior to death.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The belly of the biceps muscle (left) shows near total replacement of muscle fibres by fibro-fatty tissue while the quadriceps muscle (right) retains much more muscle tissue.
meta.OTHER NOTES: This slowly progressive muscle disorder is one of the more benign types of muscular dystrophy, being compatible with a normal life span.  It is a genetically transmitted disease with autosomal recessive pattern of inheritance.

meta.TITLE: Joint prosthesis
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Injury to ankle at age 40 was followed by rapidly progressive degenerative changes in the joint with severe pain and limitation of movement.  The ankle joint was replaced by a steel and plastic prosthesis.  The functional result was not ideal, but movement was pain free.  Patient died of a myocardial infarction 2 years later.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Section through the lower leg and posterior part of the foot, showing a stainless steel and black plastic prosthesis in situ.  The white material is plastic cement used to fix the prosthesis to the bone.  Note the lack of bony reaction to the foreign material.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Prosthetic joint replacement is well established and very successful for the hip joint, the results for the knee and ankle replacement are not so uniformly successful.

meta.TITLE: Knee
meta.SUBTITLE: LOOSE BODIES
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Football injury 18 years before operation. Since then has had intermittent "grinding" of knee with recurrent locking, pain and swelling.  Knee locked for a month prior to operation.  At operation supapatellar pouch filled with loose bodies, the articular cartilage appeared atrophied and pitted.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The loose bodies removed at operation. They are composed of cartilage with areas of calcification.  They are derived from fragments of damaged semilunar cartilage or articular cartilage from bone ends.

meta.TITLE: Knee joint
meta.SUBTITLE: OSTEOARTHRITIS
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Had suffered from pain and stiffness of the knees for a number of years, which had been attributed to osteoarthritis.  He also had severe atherosclerosis of the leg arteries and developed gangrene of the right foot.  An above knee amputation was performed.  Subsequent history is not known.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A coronal section through the knee joint and the lower condyles of the femur mounted above it showing degenerative changes typical of osteoarthritis.  The changes are best seen on the posterior surface of the patella where there is erosion of cartilage, fibrillation of the remaining fragments of cartilage at the periphery, and eburnation of the underlying bone.  The condyles of the femur show similar changes.  The tibial articular cartilage is reduced in thickness and shows fibrillation.  There is some hypertrophy and fatty infiltration of the synovial membrane.

meta.TITLE: Malignant synovioma of wrist
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Complained of a rapidly developing painless swelling in the proximal part of the right hypothenar eminence of the right hand. On examination this was initially thought to be cystic and likely to be a ganglion cyst. No fluid was obtained on aspiration of the swelling so a biopsy was performed which showed a malignant synovioma. A partial amputation of the right hand, preserving the thumb and first two fingers was performed.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A sagittal section through the amputation specimen showing a white lobulated tumour mass arising from the anterior aspect of the carpus. The tumour is well demarcated and contains a number of cystic spaces.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological section showed a malignant spindle cell tumour typical of the monophasic type of malignant synovioma.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Synovial sarcoma is a relatively uncommon tumour arising in para-articular tissues, it usually occurs in the upper and lower limbs of adolescents and young adults. Histologically they may be biphasic tumours with epithelial and spindle cell differentiation. The prognosis is poor with 5-year survivals of only 30-40%.

meta.TITLE: Knee joint
meta.SUBTITLE: SUPPURATIVE ARTHRITIS
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Fell into a ditch twelve days before admission.  Severe pain in the knee subsequently.  Admitted to hospital severely ill with pyrexia and an intensely painful swollen knee.  Died of septicaemia.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The knee joint opened to show destruction of cartilage and erosion of bone.  The joint space was full of pus and the process extended into the surrounding soft tissues.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Although not recorded in the history, it is most probable that infection was introduced via a wound related to the joint.

meta.TITLE: Pigmented villonodular synovitis
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Long history of intermittent mild pain and swelling of the right knee. Only sought medical advice when swelling of the knee became persistent. On examination there was gross swelling of the right knee joint with signs of an effusion. Movements of the knee were not restricted and there was only mild pain near the extremes of movement. Other joints appeared normal. Aspiration of the joint produced turbid rusty coloured fluid and arthroscopy and biopsy confirmed the diagnosis of pigmented villonodular synovitis. A synovectomy was performed.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Part of the operation specimen showing pigmented villous proliferation of the synovial membrane.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological sections showed gross villous proliferation of the synovial membrane with hyperplasia of synovial cells, numerous synovial giant cells, mild chronic inflammation and extensive haemosiderin pigmentation.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Pigmented villonodular synovitis is a rare condition of uncertain aetiology. Its pathological features are compatible with either a reactive process or a benign neoplastic process. It is in most cases confined to large joints but can occasionally spread locally in soft tissues.

meta.TITLE: Haemangioma of skull
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Complained of a painful lump on the head and on examination was found to have a well-defined symmetrical bony lump in the left parietal region.  X-ray showed expansion of the calvarium externally and internally with a spiculated pattern typical of haemangioma.  The lesion was excised surgically.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A section through the surgical specimen showing a vascular mass expanding the calvarium.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological section showed a benign tumour composed of large anastomosing vascular channels lined by flattened endothelium.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Haemangioma of bone is an uncommon tumour and can occur in any bone but is most commonly seen in the skull and the vertebral column.

meta.TITLE: Paget's disease
meta.SUBTITLE: SKULL
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Had suffered from Paget's disease of bone affecting the skull, pelvis and tibiae for 30 years.  Symptoms were mainly related to the disease in the skull with head and facial pain.  She also had increasing deafness thought to be associated with pressure on cranial nerve VIII by the thickened bone of the base of the skull.  She collapsed and died suddenly at home and at autopsy was found to have a ruptured dissecting aneurysm of the aorta.  This is not related in any way to the Paget's disease.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The skull cap showing gross thickening of the bone typical of Paget's disease.  The skullcap weighed 2,065gm.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Paget's disease is of unknown aetiology and can affect any bone.  Minor disease detected only by radiology is very common in elderly people but severe symptomatic disease as in this case is rare.

meta.TITLE: Paget's disease
meta.SUBTITLE: SKULL
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Died of a suppurative arthritis and septicaemia.  He had previously noticed that his legs were becoming bowed and that his skull was enlarging.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A segment of grossly thickened calvarium.  The bone is spongy and soft and the normal clear distinction between compact and cancellous bone is lost.

meta.TITLE: Metastases thoracic spine
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: This was a 52-year-old man who presented with pain in the left hip, thigh and knee diagnosed initially as sciatica. This was treated with traction but spread to both lower limbs. He then developed paraplegia and underwent a spinal cord decompression. He was given some radiation therapy but deteriorated and died. The cause of death and the remaining autopsy findings were, unfortunately, not available.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The specimen consists of Tl to T5. The cut surfaces of all the vertebral bodies show metastatic deposits.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: The only histological information available is that this is a focally very necrotic-appearing secondary malignant neoplasm.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Unfortunately, we do not have any information available as to the possible primary site of these metastatic deposits (WGE).

meta.TITLE: Metastatic carcinoma vertebral column
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: This patient presented at the age of 55 years with symptoms of mild prostatism.  He was found to have an enlarged firm prostate and a transurethal resection of prostate was performed.  Histology of the resected fragments showed extensive invasion by adenocarcinoma of prostate.  A skeletal survey showed that bone metastases were present.  Bilateral orchidectomy was performed and he was commenced on oestrogen therapy.  Over the following two years he had several palliative courses of DXR to painful bone metastases with good symptomatic relief.  Three years after diagnosis he developed paraplegia with a sensory level at T4.  A myelogram showed cord compression by metastases at T4, T6 and L5 levels.  While awaiting radiotherapy his condition deteriorated rapidly and he was thought to have a septicaemia.  Despite antibiotic therapy he died 24 hours later.  At autopsy he was found to have peritonitis due to a perforated duodenal ulcer.  Multiple bony metastases were present but no lung or liver metastases were found.  Residual primary tumour was present in the prostate.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A coronal section through the thoracic spine showing on the front surface of the specimen displacement and compression of the spinal cord at the level of T4 by tumour tissue growing into the spinal canal.  On the back surface multiple pale metastatic deposits can be seen in the vertebral bodies.
meta.OTHER NOTES: Carcinoma of the prostate commonly metastasises to bone and deposits are particularly frequent in the vertebral bodies.  This is thought to be due to communications between the prostatic and vertebral venous plexuses.

meta.TITLE: Metastatic carcinoma
meta.SUBTITLE: VERTEBRA
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Presented at age of 46 years with a lump in the breast, which on biopsy was shown to be an infiltrating duct carcinoma of the breast?  A modified radical mastectomy was performed and metastases were found in axillary lymph nodes.  There was no evidence of distant metastases at the time of operation but within twelve months she developed back pain and was shown to have bony metastases.  She was treated with chemotherapy and local radiotherapy to painful bony deposits but her general condition deteriorated progressively and she died with widespread metastatic disease.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A section through the vertebral column showing multiple white tumour deposits in lower thoracic and lumbar vertebrae.  Note that the deposits do not involve the intervertebral discs, this is an important distinguishing point between tuberculosis of bone and metastatic tumour.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological section confirmed extensive invasion of bone by poorly differentiated carcinoma similar to that originally seen in the breast tumour.

meta.TITLE: Metastatic carcinoma
meta.SUBTITLE: VERTEBRAL COLUMN
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: In 1970 this woman had a mastectomy for carcinoma of the left breast and in 1974 because of metastatic disease she had an oophorectomy.  In June 1975 she was commenced on chemotherapy and she was admitted to hospital in July 1976 with multiple bony secondaries for terminal care.  She died approximately one month after admission from a chest infection.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Coronal section through lower thoracic and upper lumbar spine shows multiple white metastatic deposits in the bone.  These were very hard on palpation characteristic of osteoblastic secondaries.  Cancer of the breast most commonly produces osteolytic metastases in bone.  Osteoblastic metastases are more often seen from prostatic carcinoma.

meta.TITLE: Spine
meta.SUBTITLE: METASTATIC TUMOUR
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Carcinoma of left breast removed at age 50 years.  Remained well for 5 years and then presented with weight loss and jaundice.  The liver was grossly enlarged and chest X-ray showed multiple lung and bone deposits.  She developed paraplegia and deteriorated rapidly.  Autopsy showed replacement of liver by tumour and multiple deposits in lung and bone.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Oblique section through the cervical spine showing multiple deposits of tumour within bone and a large sub-dural deposit which is compressing the spinal cord.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological section showed poorly differentiated carcinoma compatible with an origin in the breast.

meta.TITLE: Vertebral metastases from neuroblastoma
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Became suddenly weak in the legs and was admitted with a clinical diagnosis of poliomyelitis.  X-rays however showed collapse of thoracic vertebrae.  Operation revealed an extra dural tumour which biopsy showed neuroblastoma.  Deteriorated rapidly with evidence of metastases in other sites and severe secondary anaemia.  Autopsy revealed a primary neuroblastoma in the right adrenal with widespread metastases.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Sections through part of the thoracic spine showing one collapsed vertebrae, and white tumour deposits in at least two others.

meta.TITLE: Multiple Myeloma
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: First attended his doctor at age 56 with symptoms of general malaise.  No abnormality found on physical examination, but his ESR was found to be 60 mm/hr.  Several months later he developed back pain, at first vague in situation, but later having a girdle distribution suggesting nerve root compression.  X-ray showed several osteolytic lesions in the dorsal spine.  Serum electrophoresis showed a dense "M" band and a diagnosis of multiple myeloma was made.  Symptoms increased in severity and he developed paraplegia.  Eventually died of bronchopneumonia and uraemia.  At autopsy was found to have extensive skeletal deposits of myeloma and amyloid disease of the kidneys.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A sagittal section through the dorsal spine showing complete replacement of one vertebrae by reddish tumour tissue and a smaller deposit of similar tumour in an adjacent vertebrae.  The spinal cord is compressed and distorted at the site of the larger deposit.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: Histological section showed tumour tissue composed of uniform sheets of atypical plasma cells.

meta.TITLE: Paget's disease of rib
meta.SUBTITLE: OSTEOSARCOMA
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: Had been known to have Paget's disease of bone for twenty years.  Pronounced bowing of tibiae and ulnae, and his head was abnormally large.  Admitted to hospital because of severe pain in the scapula region, radiating round the chest.  A tumour could be felt in the chest wall attached to rib and there were several swellings in the skull.  A biopsy showed undifferentiated malignant tumour.  No active treatment was undertaken and he died a few weeks later.  At autopsy in addition to the changes of Paget's disease, multiple bone tumours were found and metastatic deposits were present in the lungs.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: A large partly ossified tumour arises from a rib, which shows irregular thickening due to Paget's disease.

meta.TITLE: Hyperostosis frontalis interna
meta.CLINICAL SUMMARY: This 94-year-old woman came into hospital with dyspnoea and dullness at the left base and a white count of 19. A clinical diagnosis of bronchopneumonia was made. At post mortem the cause of death was found bilateral bronchopneumonia.
meta.MACROSCOPIC SUMMARY: This is the calvarium, which is grossly thickened and shows multiple raised bony nodules on the internal table.  These bony protrusions indented the underlying cerebral cortex. The appearances are of extensive hyperostosis frontalis interna.
meta.MICROSCOPIC SUMMARY: It shows no evidence of unusual osteoblastic or osteoelastic activity and is composed of densely sclerotic bone.
meta.KEYWORDS: HYPEROSTOSIS, FRONTALIS, INTERNA, 21.62.01, 21 62 01, 216201, F.165, F 165, F165
